HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 848
By McKenzie
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Randy Tyree of Knox
County.
WHEREAS, we were greatly saddened to learn of the passing of Randy Tyree of Knox
County; and
WHEREAS, former Knoxville Mayor Randy Tyree lived a life marked by service to his
family, community, and country, and he will be remembered for his kindness, humility, and
sense of humor; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Tyree was born in Gordonsville to a military and law enforcement family;
he attended Gordonsville High School before moving to Washington, D.C., to work for the FBI,
eventually transferring to Puerto Rico; and
WHEREAS, Randy Tyree resigned from the FBI to study at Middle Tennessee State
University, graduating in 1965 and relocating to Knoxville to attend the University of Tennessee;
shortly after arriving, he led an effort to honor the life of a pedestrian who died stopping a
runaway truck, a compassionate gesture that garnered the attention of former Knoxville Mayor
Leonard Rogers; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Tyree went on to join the Knoxville Police Department, initially serving
as a patrolman and then as a detective; his acumen and work ethic soon led to his promotion to
the post of police and fire commissioner; and
WHEREAS, in 1969, Mr. Tyree began to work on the Tennessee Law Enforcement
Planning Agency, where he served as the supervisor of judicial planning and eventually the
assistant director; and
HJR0848
011849
- 1 -

WHEREAS, the following year, Mayor Rogers appointed Randy Tyree as Knoxville's city
safety director; under Mr. Tyree's leadership, Knoxville law enforcement carried out Operation
Aquarius, a massive crackdown on illegal drugs in the State; and
WHEREAS, in 1972, Mr. Tyree joined the law firm of Egerton, Armistead, Davis, and
McCord before moving to the firm of Morrison, Morrison, Tyree, and Morrow; and
WHEREAS, Randy Tyree announced that he was running for mayor in August 1975; at
that time, he was chairman and president-elect of the Knox County Cancer Crusade and on the
boards of the Knoxville Area Urban League, Consumer Credit Counseling Service, National
Council of Christians and Jews, and Florence Crittenton Agency; and
WHEREAS, furthermore, Mr. Tyree served on the East Tennessee Law Enforcement
Planning Commission's steering committee and the Knox County Alcohol and Drug Abuse
Rehabilitation Advisory Committee; he was also a member of the Downtown Rotary Club and
West Knoxville Jaycees, who named him Outstanding Young Man of the Year; and
WHEREAS, after being elected mayor in 1975, Randy Tyree most notably brought the
World's Fair to Knoxville, something that many people said could not be done; he worked with
U.S. Presidents Gerald Ford, Jimmy Carter, and Ronald Reagan to make it happen; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Tyree stated about the fair that "it gave our community a purpose, and
an attitude of being able to accomplish something beyond the ordinary […] it unified the
community in a way that I have not seen before or since"; and
WHEREAS, Randy Tyree served as mayor from 1976 to 1984; during his tenure, he
helped bring more than 11 million visitors to the city; and
WHEREAS, in his later years, he worked for Visit Knoxville as an ambassador to the
Sunsphere and became known as one of the best parts of the Sunsphere experience; and
- 2 - 011849

WHEREAS, Randy Tyree will be sadly mourned but fondly remembered by his ex-wife
and friend, Mary Pat Tyree; four children, Niki Tyree, Scott Tyree, Chad Tyree, and Ryan Tyree;
daughter-in-law, JoElla Tyree; and grandchildren, Kaia and River; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Tyree leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in public
life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Randy Tyree, reflecting fondly upon his
impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and
conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Tyree.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
